93
00:07:08,284 --> 00:07:10,578
Hmm?

94
00:07:11,078 --> 00:07:12,539
Listen.

95
00:07:12,747 --> 00:07:14,666
If we can't break the ice...

96
00:07:15,584 --> 00:07:17,544
...how about we drown it?

97
00:07:27,721 --> 00:07:29,472
CHARLES: So what's your story?

98
00:07:30,390 --> 00:07:33,768
<i>You the poor kid that never got to go</i>
<i>to Exeter or Andover? </i>

99
00:07:34,769 --> 00:07:37,439
Despite my privileged upbringing,
I'm well-balanced.

100
00:07:37,522 --> 00:07:39,232
I have a chip on both shoulders.

101
00:07:39,316 --> 00:07:40,901
[Chuckles]

102
00:07:41,443 --> 00:07:45,030
Maybe you're just better with
the old integers than you are with people.

103
00:07:45,113 --> 00:07:48,867
JOHN: My first grade teacher said
I was born with two helpings of brain...

104
00:07:48,950 --> 00:07:50,994
...but only half a helping of heart.

105
00:07:51,077 --> 00:07:51,912
[Chuckles]

106
00:07:52,203 --> 00:07:54,539
CHARLES: Wow! She sounds lovely!

107
00:07:55,540 --> 00:07:57,375
The truth is that I...

108
00:07:57,542 --> 00:07:59,377
I don't like people much.

109
00:08:00,253 --> 00:08:01,838
And they don't much like me.

110
00:08:01,922 --> 00:08:04,883
But why,
with all your obvious wit and charm?

111
00:08:05,175 --> 00:08:06,635
[Laughs]

112
00:08:07,510 --> 00:08:09,179
Seriously, John.

113
00:08:10,931 --> 00:08:12,432
Mathematics...

114
00:08:13,516 --> 00:08:16,728
Mathematics is never going to lead you
to a higher truth.

115
00:08:16,811 --> 00:08:18,521
And you know why?

116
00:08:18,980 --> 00:08:21,608
Because it's boring. It's really boring.

117
00:08:22,776 --> 00:08:25,862
You know, half these schoolboys
are already published?

118
00:08:26,738 --> 00:08:29,408
I cannot waste time
with these classes and...

119
00:08:29,533 --> 00:08:31,285
<i>... these books. </i>

120
00:08:32,787 --> 00:08:33,537
[Coughs]

121
00:08:34,038 --> 00:08:36,666
Memorizing the weaker assumptions
of lesser mortals!

122
00:08:36,791 --> 00:08:39,085
[Chuckles]

123
00:08:39,585 --> 00:08:41,462
I need to look through...

124
00:08:41,921 --> 00:08:43,965
...to the governing dynamics.

125
00:08:48,010 --> 00:08:49,804
Find a truly original idea.

126
00:08:50,179 --> 00:08:52,640
That's the only way
I'll ever distinguish myself.

127
00:08:52,723 --> 00:08:55,434
- It's the only way that I'll ever...
- Matter.

128
00:08:58,312 --> 00:08:59,939
Yes.

129
00:09:01,732 --> 00:09:04,652
MARTIN: All right, who's next?
SOL: I've played enough go for today.

130
00:09:04,735 --> 00:09:06,487
- Come on.
- I hate this game.

131
00:09:06,571 --> 00:09:08,239
Cowards, all of you!

132
00:09:08,322 --> 00:09:10,491
None of you rise to meet my challenge?

133
00:09:10,575 --> 00:09:14,120
Come on, Bender. Whoever wins,
Sol does his laundry all semester.

134
00:09:14,203 --> 00:09:17,206
- Does that seem unfair to anyone else?
- Not at all.

135
00:09:19,417 --> 00:09:21,377
MARTIN: Look at him.
BENDER: Nash!

136
00:09:21,460 --> 00:09:23,296
Taking a reverse constitutional?

137
00:09:23,379 --> 00:09:26,841
I'm hoping to extract an algorithm
to define their movement.

138
00:09:30,136 --> 00:09:31,178
Oh.

139
00:09:31,846 --> 00:09:32,888
Psycho.

140
00:09:34,098 --> 00:09:37,518
SOL: I thought you dropped out.
You ever going to go to class or...

141
00:09:37,602 --> 00:09:39,896
Classes will dull your mind.

142
00:09:40,479 --> 00:09:43,149
Destroy the potential
for authentic creativity.

143
00:09:43,232 --> 00:09:44,901
Oh, I didn't know that.

144
00:09:44,984 --> 00:09:47,321
Nash is going to stun us all
with his genius.

145
00:09:47,905 --> 00:09:51,742
Which is another way of saying
he doesn't have the nerve to compete.

146
00:09:53,285 --> 00:09:54,536
You scared?

147
00:09:54,620 --> 00:09:57,247
Terrified. Mortified. Petrified.

148
00:09:57,331 --> 00:09:58,999
Stupefied by you.

149
00:10:00,208 --> 00:10:01,627
No starch.

150
00:10:01,710 --> 00:10:03,712
Pressed and folded.

151
00:10:06,632 --> 00:10:08,675
Let me ask you something, John.

152
00:10:08,967 --> 00:10:10,344
Be my guest, Martin.

153
00:10:10,427 --> 00:10:14,514
Bender and Sol here correctly completed
Allen's proof of Perron's conjectures.

154
00:10:14,598 --> 00:10:16,266
JOHN: Adequate work...

155
00:10:17,059 --> 00:10:18,727
...without innovation.

156
00:10:18,852 --> 00:10:21,521
- I'm flattered. You flattered?
- Flattered.

157
00:10:21,605 --> 00:10:25,859
MARTIN: And I've got two weapons briefs
under security review by the DOD.

158
00:10:26,026 --> 00:10:27,903
Derivative drivel.

159
00:10:29,404 --> 00:10:32,282
But Nash achievements: zero.

160
00:10:32,366 --> 00:10:35,494
I'm a patient man, Martin.
Is there an actual question coming?

161
00:10:37,079 --> 00:10:40,082
What if you never come up
with your original idea?

162
00:10:42,376 --> 00:10:45,128
MARTIN: How will it feel
when I'm chosen for Wheeler...

163
00:10:45,963 --> 00:10:47,381
...and you're not?

164
00:10:50,759 --> 00:10:52,386
What if you lose?

165
00:11:03,690 --> 00:11:05,024
You should not have won.

166
00:11:05,108 --> 00:11:05,858
Hmm.

167
00:11:06,401 --> 00:11:08,987
I had the first move, my play was perfect.

168
00:11:09,070 --> 00:11:10,780
The hubris of the defeated.

169
00:11:10,863 --> 00:11:12,448
The game is flawed.

170
00:11:19,038 --> 00:11:22,000
MARTIN: Gentlemen, the great John Nash.

171
00:11:28,423 --> 00:11:30,967
CHARLES: You've been in here
for two days.

172
00:11:33,720 --> 00:11:36,431
You know Hansen
has just published another paper?

173
00:11:36,514 --> 00:11:39,100
I can't even find a topic for my doctorate.

174
00:11:40,977 --> 00:11:43,771
