00:16:35,567 --> 00:16:40,364
I'm sorry, but up to this point, your record
doesn't warrant any placement at all.

248
00:16:44,284 --> 00:16:46,078
Good day.

249
00:16:56,088 --> 00:16:58,340
PROFESSOR:
And my compliments to you, sir.

250
00:16:58,590 --> 00:17:00,217
MAX: Thank you so much.

251
00:17:01,260 --> 00:17:03,345
[Poignant instrumental music]

252
00:17:17,568 --> 00:17:19,278
JOHN: I can't see it.

253
00:17:19,736 --> 00:17:21,697
[Whimpers]

254
00:17:26,618 --> 00:17:28,329
CHARLES: Jesus Christ, John.

255
00:17:29,581 --> 00:17:30,999
I can't fail.

256
00:17:31,165 --> 00:17:33,835
JOHN: This is all I am.
CHARLES: Come on, let's go out.

257
00:17:33,960 --> 00:17:35,878
- I have to get something done.
- John!

258
00:17:35,962 --> 00:17:39,215
- I can't keep staring into space.
- John, enough!

259
00:17:39,340 --> 00:17:43,553
JOHN: Got to face the wall,
follow their rules, read their books...

260
00:17:43,636 --> 00:17:45,722
...do their classes.

261
00:17:45,888 --> 00:17:48,391
Come on! Go on, bust your head!
Kill yourself.

262
00:17:49,100 --> 00:17:51,477
CHARLES: Don't do it. Don't mess around.

263
00:17:51,561 --> 00:17:55,315
Bust your head! Go on,
bust that worthless head wide open.

264
00:17:55,398 --> 00:17:58,568
JOHN: Goddamn it, Charles!
What the hell is your problem?

265
00:18:01,654 --> 00:18:03,239
It's not my problem.

266
00:18:05,366 --> 00:18:07,201
And it's not your problem.

267
00:18:10,580 --> 00:18:12,248
It's their problem.

268
00:18:12,457 --> 00:18:15,543
CHARLES: Your answer isn't,
"face the wall."

269
00:18:16,252 --> 00:18:17,795
<i>It's out there... </i>

270
00:18:18,338 --> 00:18:20,298
<i>... where you've been working. </i>

271
00:18:36,522 --> 00:18:37,857
[John gasps]

272
00:18:41,236 --> 00:18:42,904
That was heavy.

273
00:18:46,492 --> 00:18:48,661
That Isaac Newton fellow was right.

274
00:18:48,911 --> 00:18:50,829
- He was onto something.
- Clever boy.

275
00:18:50,913 --> 00:18:51,914
[Giggles]

276
00:18:51,997 --> 00:18:55,584
JOHN: Don't worry, that's mine.
I'll come and get it in a minute.

277
00:18:55,709 --> 00:18:58,045
CHARLES: [Laughing] Oh, God.

278
00:19:01,215 --> 00:19:03,759
NEILSON: Incoming, gentlemen.
SOL: Ay-yi-yi.

279
00:19:08,389 --> 00:19:09,807
Deep breaths.

280
00:19:10,641 --> 00:19:14,687
SOL: Nash, you might want to stop
shuffling your papers for five seconds.

281
00:19:18,774 --> 00:19:20,693
I will not buy you gentlemen beer.

282
00:19:20,776 --> 00:19:23,320
BENDER: We're not here for beer,
my friend.

283
00:19:24,405 --> 00:19:26,323
JOHN: Oh.

284
00:19:27,908 --> 00:19:31,245
Does anyone else feel
she should be moving in slow motion?

285
00:19:31,787 --> 00:19:33,914
Will she want a large wedding, you think?

286
00:19:33,998 --> 00:19:36,166
Shall we say swords? Pistols at dawn?

287
00:19:36,250 --> 00:19:38,002
Have you remembered nothing?

288
00:19:38,711 --> 00:19:40,921
<i>Recall the lessons of Adam Smith... </i>

289
00:19:41,088 --> 00:19:43,257
...the father of modern economics.

290
00:19:43,841 --> 00:19:44,883
"In competition...

291
00:19:44,967 --> 00:19:47,845
SOL<i>I</i>NEILSON: "...individual ambition
serves the common good."

292
00:19:47,928 --> 00:19:49,888
Every man for himself, gentlemen.

293
00:19:49,972 --> 00:19:52,558
BENDER: Those who strike out
are stuck with her friends.

294
00:19:52,641 --> 00:19:54,310
MARTIN: I'm not going to strike out.

295
00:19:54,393 --> 00:19:57,479
SOL: You can lead a blonde to water,
but you can't make her drink.

296
00:19:57,563 --> 00:19:58,981
SOL: Nobody move.

297
00:19:59,106 --> 00:20:01,859
<i>She's looking over here. </i>
<i>She's looking at Nash. </i>

298
00:20:02,067 --> 00:20:04,321
MARTIN: Oh, God.
He may have the upper hand now...

299
00:20:04,404 --> 00:20:06,448
<i>... but wait until he opens his mouth. </i>

300
00:20:06,531 --> 00:20:08,450
<i>Remember the last time? </i>

301
00:20:08,533 --> 00:20:10,785
BENDER: That was one
for the history books.

302
00:20:17,292 --> 00:20:20,503
- Adam Smith needs revision.
- What are you talking about?

303
00:20:21,796 --> 00:20:23,798
If we all go for the blonde...

304
00:20:28,553 --> 00:20:30,347
<i>... we block each other. </i>

305
00:20:30,430 --> 00:20:33,391
<i>Not a single one of us is going to get her. </i>

306
00:20:34,100 --> 00:20:36,186
<i>So then we go for her friends... </i>

307
00:20:37,771 --> 00:20:42,651
<i>... but they will all give us the cold shoulder</i>
<i>because nobody likes to be second choice. </i>

308
00:20:42,734 --> 00:20:45,237
Well, what if no one goes for the blonde?

309
00:20:47,113 --> 00:20:49,324
<i>We don't get in each other's way... </i>

310
00:20:49,491 --> 00:20:51,910
<i>... and we don't insult the other girls. </i>

311
00:20:53,286 --> 00:20:55,288
That's the only way we win.

312
00:20:57,540 --> 00:20:59,417
That's the only way we all get laid.

313
00:20:59,542 --> 00:21:01,044
[Chuckles]

314
00:21:04,965 --> 00:21:06,716
Adam Smith said:

315
00:21:06,925 --> 00:21:08,927
"The best result comes...

316
00:21:09,844 --> 00:21:13,056
"...from everyone in the group
doing what's best for himself."

317
00:21:13,139 --> 00:21:15,809
Right. Incomplete. Okay?

318
00:21:16,601 --> 00:21:19,145
Because the best result will come...

319
00:21:20,398 --> 00:21:22,441
...from everyone in the group...

320
00:21:22,525 --> 00:21:24,735
...doing what's best for himself...

321
00:21:25,444 --> 00:21:26,612
...and the group.

322
00:21:26,696 --> 00:21:29,782
If this is some way for you
to get the blonde, go to hell.

323
00:21:29,865 --> 00:21:33,286
Governing dynamics. Adam Smith...

324
00:21:34,787 --> 00:21:36,539
...was wrong.

325
00:21:36,622 --> 00:21:38,958
SOL: Here we go.
NEILSON: Careful, careful.

326
00:21:41,627 --> 00:21:42,962
Thank you.

327
00:21:55,141 --> 00:21:57,810
"C" of "S" equals "C" of "T."

328
00:22:00,021 --> 00:22:01,606
[Indistinct muttering]

329
00:22:07,069 --> 00:22:09,155
[Muttering continues]

330
00:22:26,589 --> 00:22:30,217
[Dramatic instrumental music]

331
00:23:00,749 --> 00:23:04,336
You do realize this flies in the face
of 150 years of economic theory?

332
00:23:04,419 --> 00:23:05,545
Yes, I do, sir.

333
00:23:05,629 --> 00:23:08,882
- That's rather presumptuous, no?
- It is, sir.

334
00:23:16,056 --> 00:23:17,891
Well, Mr. Nash...

335
00:23:18,475 --> 00:23:21,103
<i>... with a breakthrough of this magnitude... </i>

336
00:23:21,228 --> 00:23:24,314
<i>... I'm confident you will get</i>
<i>any placement you like. </i>

337
00:23:31,154 --> 00:23:32,906
<i>Wheeler Labs... </i>

338
00:23:33,824 --> 00:23:36,618
<i>... they'll ask you to recommend</i>
<i>two team members. </i>

339
00:23:40,330 --> 00:23:42,624
PROFESSOR: Stills and Frank
are excellent choices.

340
00:23:42,708 --> 00:23:44,585
Sol and Bender, sir.

341
00:23:44,668 --> 00:23:48,255
Sol and Bender
are extraordinary mathematicians.

342
00:23:48,338 --> 00:23:52,843
Has it occurred to you that Sol and Bender
might have plans of their own?

343
00:23:56,598 --> 00:23:58,016
BENDER: [Laughing] We made it!

344
00:23:58,099 --> 00:24:00,059
Wheeler, we made it!

345
00:24:00,935 --> 00:24:02,895
Cheers, cheers, cheers!

346
00:24:05,231 --> 00:24:07,442
Okay, awkward moment, gentlemen.

347
00:24:27,962 --> 00:24:29,422
Umm...

348
00:24:32,258 --> 00:24:33,843
Governing dynamics.

349
00:24:37,055 --> 00:24:38,556
MARTIN: Congratulations, John.

350
00:24:38,640 --> 00:24:41,684
BENDER: Toast! To Wheeler Labs!
SOL: To Wheeler!

351
00:24:53,905 --> 00:24:56,950
THE PENTAGON 1953 - FIVE YEARS LATER

352
00:25:06,501 --> 00:25:09,212
MAN: General, the analyst
from Wheeler Lab is here.

353
00:25:09,295 --> 00:25:11,048
Dr. Nash, your coat?

354
00:25:11,131 --> 00:25:12,508
Thank you, sir.

355
00:25:14,301 --> 00:25:17,012
General, this is Wheeler team leader,
Dr. John Nash.

356
00:25:17,096 --> 00:25:19,682
- Glad you could come, Doctor.
- Hello.

357
00:25:20,808 --> 00:25:22,309
Right this way.

358
00:25:22,726 --> 00:25:26,188
GENERAL: We've been intercepting
radio transmissions from Moscow.

359
00:25:27,106 --> 00:25:30,567
<i>The computer can't detect a pattern, </i>
<i>but I'm sure it's code. </i>

360
00:25:31,360 --> 00:25:33,028
JOHN: Why is that, General?

361
00:25:33,571 --> 00:25:36,073
GENERAL: Ever just know something,
Dr. Nash?

362
00:25:38,367 --> 00:25:39,785
Constantly.

363
00:25:42,204 --> 00:25:44,373
GENERAL: We've developed
several ciphers.

364
00:25:46,083 --> 00:25:48,836
<i>If you'd like to review</i>
<i>our preliminary data? </i>

365
00:25:50,963 --> 00:25:53,424
GENERAL: Doctor?
JOHN: [Voiceover] 6-7-3-7.

366
00:25:53,716 --> 00:25:55,676
<i>0- 3-6... </i>

367
00:26:09,273 --> 00:26:11,275
<i>8- 4-9-4.</i>

368
00:26:41,014 --> 00:26:43,099
<i>9- 1-4-0-3-4.</i>

369
00:27:00,867 --> 00:27:02,494
I need a map.

370
00:27:04,955 --> 00:27:08,917
JOHN: 46-13-08, 67-46-90.

371
00:27:11,336 --> 00:27:13,046
<i>Starkey Corners, Maine. </i>

372
00:27:14,297 --> 00:27:16,091
48-03-01.

373
00:27:16,174 --> 00:27:19,094
91-26-35.

374
00:27:20,220 --> 00:27:22,013
<i>Prairie Portage, Minnesota. </i>

375
00:27:22,389 --> 00:27:24,599
These are latitudes and longitudes.

376
00:27:24,933 --> 00:27:26,601
There are at least 10 others.

377
00:27:26,685 --> 00:27:30,313
They appear to be routing orders
across the border into the U.S.

378
00:27:31,439 --> 00:27:32,983
Extraordinary.

379
00:27:33,817 --> 00:27:36,820
Gentlemen, we need to move on this.

380
00:27:39,030 --> 00:27:43,076
- Who's Big Brother?
- You've done your country a great service.

381
00:27:43,577 --> 00:27:45,246
- Captain!
- Yes, sir.

382
00:27:46,706 --> 00:27:49,041
Accompany Dr. Nash.

383
00:27:49,166 --> 00:27:51,544
What are the Russians moving, General?

384
00:27:52,461 --> 00:27:55,798
Captain Rogers will escort you
to the unrestricted area, Doctor.

385
00:27:55,881 --> 00:27:57,008
<i>Thank you. </i>

386
00:27:57,800 --> 00:28:00,136
ROGERS: Dr. Nash, follow me, please.

387
00:28:07,018 --> 00:28:10,104
[Over radio] <i>None of those</i>
<i>who said they don't like the method... </i>

388
00:28:10,187 --> 00:28:14,233
<i>... have told us any other method</i>
<i>they could use that would be effective. </i>

389
00:28:15,151 --> 00:28:17,445
DRIVER: It's Dr. Nash.
GUARD: All right.

390
00:28:23,618 --> 00:28:27,455
WHEELER DEFENSE LABS
MIT CAMPUS

391
00:28:31,709 --> 00:28:33,961
- Thank you, sir.
- Home run at the Pentagon?

392
00:28:34,045 --> 00:28:37,506
Have they actually taken the word
"classified" out of the dictionary?

393
00:28:37,798 --> 00:28:40,009
Hi. The air conditioning broke again.

394
00:28:40,092 --> 00:28:43,262
How am I supposed to be in here
saving the world if I'm melting?

395
00:28:43,346 --> 00:28:44,931
Our hearts go out to you.

396
00:28:45,681 --> 00:28:48,517
Two trips to the Pentagon in four years.

397
00:28:48,601 --> 00:28:51,187
- That's two more than we've had.
- It gets better.

398
00:28:51,270 --> 00:28:53,940
Just got our latest
scintillating assignment.

399
00:28:54,482 --> 00:28:58,736
You know, the Russians have the H-bomb,
the Nazis are repatriating South America...

400
00:28:58,819 --> 00:29:01,906
...the Chinese have a standing army
of 2.8 million...

401
00:29:01,990 --> 00:29:04,952
...and I am doing stress tests on a dam.

402
00:29:05,535 --> 00:29:07,913
You made the cover of <i>Fortune</i> again.

403
00:29:07,996 --> 00:29:10,874
Please note the use of the word "you,"
not "we."

404
00:29:11,917 --> 00:29:14,002
That was supposed to be just me.

405
00:29:14,795 --> 00:29:16,713
[Chuckles]

406
00:29:17,005 --> 00:29:19,216
Not only do they rob me
of the Fields' Medal...

407
00:29:19,299 --> 00:29:22,636
...they put me on the cover
of <i>Fortune</i> magazine with these hacks...

408
00:29:22,719 --> 00:29:24,388
...these scholars of trivia.

409
00:29:24,596 --> 00:29:28,350
Exactly what's the difference
between genius and most genius?

410
00:29:29,142 --> 00:29:30,352
Quite a lot.

411
00:29:31,061 --> 00:29:34,147
He's your son.
Anyway, you've got 10 minutes.

412
00:29:34,231 --> 00:29:37,484
JOHN: I've always got 10 minutes.
BENDER: Before your new class?

413
00:29:43,865 --> 00:29:46,702
Can I not get a note
from a doctor or something?

414
00:29:47,077 --> 00:29:49,329
You are a doctor, John, and no.

415
00:29:49,913 --> 00:29:52,749
You know the drill,
we get these beautiful facilities...

416
00:29:52,833 --> 00:29:56,962
...MIT gets America's great minds of today,
teaching their great minds of tomorrow.

417
00:29:57,045 --> 00:30:00,340
- Poor bastards.
- Now, have a nice day at school.

418
00:30:00,549 --> 00:30:02,009
The bell is ringing.

419
00:30:11,476 --> 00:30:13,520
[Door opens]

420
00:30:23,781 --> 00:30:25,950
The eager young minds of tomorrow.

421
00:30:26,284 --> 00:30:28,161
[Loud jack-hammering outside]

422
00:30:36,044 --> 00:30:39,339
STUDENT: Can we leave one open,
Professor? It's really hot, sir.

423
00:30:41,466 --> 00:30:45,094
Your comfort comes second
to my ability to hear my own voice.

424
00:30:50,642 --> 00:30:51,893
JOHN: Personally...

425
00:30:52,852 --> 00:30:56,731
<i>... I think this class will be</i>
<i>a waste of your... </i>

426
00:30:56,814 --> 00:30:58,816
<i>... and what is infinitely worse... </i>

427
00:31:00,276 --> 00:31:01,611
...my time.

428
00:31:03,488 --> 00:31:06,157
However, here we are.

429
00:31:06,241 --> 00:31:09,160
So you may attend or not.

430
00:31:10,286 --> 00:31:13,039
You may complete your assignments
at your whim.

431
00:31:13,122 --> 00:31:14,457
<i>We have begun. </i>

432
00:31:17,585 --> 00:31:18,461
Miss.

433
00:31:22,215 --> 00:31:23,383
ALICIA: Excuse me!

434
00:31:24,217 --> 00:31:26,386
ALICIA: Excuse me!
FOREMAN: Hey, hey!

435
00:31:26,636 --> 00:31:27,512
ALICIA: Hi!

436
00:31:29,681 --> 00:31:31,099
<i>We have a little problem. </i>

437
00:31:31,182 --> 00:31:33,977
<i>It's extremely hot in here</i>
<i>with the windows closed... </i>

438
00:31:34,060 --> 00:31:36,438
<i>... and extremely noisy with them open. </i>

439
00:31:36,522 --> 00:31:39,108
<i>I was wondering</i>
<i>if there was any way you could... </i>

440
00:31:39,191 --> 00:31:42,736
<i>... I don't know, maybe work</i>
<i>someplace else for about 45 minutes? </i>

441
00:31:43,195 --> 00:31:45,906
FOREMAN: Not a problem.
ALICIA: Thank you so much!

442
00:31:45,990 --> 00:31:47,908
FOREMAN: Break!
WORKER: Got it!

443
00:31:48,158 --> 00:31:50,744
FOREMAN: Let's go. Clean it up a little bit.

444
00:31:52,663 --> 00:31:56,166
As you will find in multivariable calculus,
there is often...

445
00:31:57,167 --> 00:31:59,920
...a number of solutions
for any given problem.

446
00:32:03,716 --> 00:32:06,051
As I was saying, this problem here...

447
00:32:06,885 --> 00:32:09,555
<i>... will take some of you</i>
<i>many months to solve. </i>

448
00:32:10,264 --> 00:32:11,974
For others among you...

449
00:32:13,517 --> 00:32:16,520
...it will take you the term
of your natural lives.

450
00:32:30,200 --> 00:32:31,535
PARCHER: Professor Nash.

451
00:32:45,215 --> 00:32:46,800
William Parcher.

452
00:32:47,676 --> 00:32:48,928
Big Brother...

453
00:32:50,763 --> 00:32:52,264
<i>... at your service. </i>

454
00:32:52,556 --> 00:32:55,185
What can I do
for the Department of Defense?

455
00:32:55,518 --> 00:32:58,688
- Are you here to give me a raise?
- Let's take a walk.

456
00:33:00,065 --> 00:33:02,984
- Impressive work at the Pentagon.
- Yes, it was.

457
00:33:03,318 --> 00:33:07,072
Oppenheimer used to say, "A genius
sees the answer before the question."

458
00:33:07,155 --> 00:33:08,740
You knew Oppenheimer?

459
00:33:09,157 --> 00:33:11,493
His project was under my supervision.

460
00:33:12,077 --> 00:33:13,328
Which project?

461
00:33:16,623 --> 00:33:19,334
JOHN: That project.
PARCHER: It's not that simple.

462
00:33:19,584 --> 00:33:21,127
Well, you ended the war.

463
00:33:21,211 --> 00:33:24,756
We incinerated 150,000 people
in a heartbeat.

464
00:33:24,839 --> 00:33:27,676
Great deeds come at great cost,
Mr. Parcher.

465
00:33:28,802 --> 00:33:34,015
Conviction, it turns out, is a luxury
of those on the sidelines, Mr. Nash.

466
00:33:36,268 --> 00:33:38,311
I'll try and keep that in mind.

467
00:33:41,231 --> 00:33:43,566
PARCHER: So, John, no family...

468
00:33:44,234 --> 00:33:46,069
<i>... no close friends. </i>

469
00:33:46,569 --> 00:33:50,323
PARCHER: Why is that?
JOHN: I like to think it's because I'm a Ione wolf.

470
00:33:51,491 --> 00:33:54,160
But mainly it's because
people don't like me.

471
00:33:54,244 --> 00:33:55,370
[Chuckles]

472
00:33:55,453 --> 00:33:57,080
There are certain endeavors...

473
00:33:57,163 --> 00:34:01,167
...where your lack of personal connection
would be considered an advantage.

474
00:34:03,336 --> 00:34:06,089
JOHN: This is a secure area.
PARCHER: They know me.

475
00:34:09,092 --> 00:34:10,511
PARCHER: Have you ever been here?

476
00:34:10,595 --> 00:34:14,515
JOHN: We were told in our initial briefing
these warehouses were abandoned.

477
00:34:14,599 --> 00:34:16,767
PARCHER: That's not precisely accurate.

478
00:34:23,065 --> 00:34:25,818
[Low radio chatter]

479
00:34:32,533 --> 00:34:34,619
[Dramatic instrumental music]

480
00:34:38,414 --> 00:34:40,666
[Radio transmits Russian speaker]

481
00:34:53,930 --> 00:34:55,932
PARCHER: By telling you this...

482
00:34:56,015 --> 00:34:59,393
<i>... I am increasing your security clearance</i>
<i>to top secret. </i>

483
00:34:59,477 --> 00:35:03,147
Disclosure of secure information
can result in imprisonment.

484
00:35:03,606 --> 00:35:04,607
Get it?

485
00:35:05,483 --> 00:35:06,943
What operation?

486
00:35:12,573 --> 00:35:14,158
Those are a good idea.

487
00:35:18,329 --> 00:35:22,041
PARCHER: This factory is in Berlin,
we seized it at the end of the war.

488
00:35:22,124 --> 00:35:25,670
<i>Nazi engineers were attempting to build</i>
<i>a portable atomic bomb. </i>

489
00:35:26,170 --> 00:35:30,592
The Soviets reached this facility
before we did, and we lost the damn thing.

490
00:35:33,011 --> 00:35:35,347
The routing orders at the Pentagon.

491
00:35:36,265 --> 00:35:38,642
They were about this, weren't they?

492
00:35:38,725 --> 00:35:41,186
The Soviets aren't as unified
as people believe.

493
00:35:41,270 --> 00:35:44,481
PARCHER: A faction of the Red Army
calling itself <i>Novaya Svoboda</i>...

494
00:35:44,564 --> 00:35:47,150
...the "New Freedom,"
has control of the bomb...

495
00:35:47,234 --> 00:35:49,861
...and intends to detonate it on U.S. soil.

496
00:35:50,862 --> 00:35:54,199
Their plan is to incur
maximum civilian casualties.

497
00:35:58,579 --> 00:36:02,541
PARCHER: Man is capable of as much atrocity
as he has imagination.

498
00:36:04,459 --> 00:36:07,754
<i>New Freedom has sleeper agents</i>
<i>here in the U.S. </i>

499
00:36:09,131 --> 00:36:12,593
McCarthy is an idiot, but, unfortunately,
that doesn't make him wrong.

500
00:36:14,428 --> 00:36:16,555
<i>New Freedom communicates</i>
<i>to its agents... </i>

501
00:36:16,638 --> 00:36:19,808
...through codes imbedded in newspapers
and magazines...

502
00:36:19,891 --> 00:36:21,602
...and that's where you come in.

503
00:36:21,685 --> 00:36:25,147
<i>You see, John, what distinguishes you... </i>

504
00:36:26,023 --> 00:36:28,734
...is that you are, quite simply...

505
00:36:29,318 --> 00:36:32,654
...the best natural code-breaker
I have ever seen.

506
00:36:38,785 --> 00:36:41,622
What exactly is it
that you would like me to do?

507
00:36:47,045 --> 00:36:50,089
Commit this list of periodicals to memory.

508
00:36:51,424 --> 00:36:55,261
PARCHER: Scan each new issue,
find any hidden codes, decipher them.

509
00:36:58,598 --> 00:37:00,892
DOCTOR: Place your chin on the chin rest.

510
00:37:00,975 --> 00:37:04,395
DOCTOR: Stare into the light.
TECHNICIAN: Pulse 88, regular.

511
00:37:07,732 --> 00:37:10,234
DOCTOR: Okay, this may be
a little uncomfortable.

512
00:37:10,318 --> 00:37:12,278
[Groans]

513
00:37:12,403 --> 00:37:14,948
PARCHER: It's got a little zap to it,
doesn't it?

514
00:37:15,365 --> 00:37:18,076
He just implanted a radium diode.

515
00:37:18,284 --> 00:37:19,994
Don't worry, it's safe.

516
00:37:20,620 --> 00:37:22,664
<i>The isotope decays predictably. </i>

517
00:37:22,956 --> 00:37:26,125
<i>As a result, </i>
<i>these numbers change over time. </i>

518
00:37:26,542 --> 00:37:29,254
They're the access codes to your drop spot.

519
00:37:31,214 --> 00:37:33,967
So what am I now, a spy?

520
00:37:46,229 --> 00:37:47,438
[Knock at door]

521
00:37:47,522 --> 00:37:48,564
JOHN: Come.

522
00:37:52,568 --> 00:37:55,238
Boy, you must be really important.

523
00:38:03,163 --> 00:38:05,332
It's all right, Mike.

524
00:38:14,883 --> 00:38:16,594
What are you working on?

525
00:38:18,637 --> 00:38:19,972
Classified.

526
00:38:21,599 --> 00:38:23,559
Everyone waited half an hour.

527
00:38:23,642 --> 00:38:26,395
JOHN: For?
ALICIA: Class.

528
00:38:27,313 --> 00:38:28,897
<i>You missed class today. </i>

529
00:38:29,898 --> 00:38:32,776
Oh. I suspect that...

530
00:38:34,069 --> 00:38:36,614
...nobody missed me.

531
00:38:36,697 --> 00:38:39,241
ALICIA: The problem
that you left on the board...

532
00:38:40,868 --> 00:38:42,036
...I solved it.

533
00:38:42,995 --> 00:38:45,831
- No, you didn't.
- You didn't even look.

534
00:38:46,957 --> 00:38:50,419
I never said that the vector fields
were rational functions.

535
00:38:54,798 --> 00:38:56,550
Your solution is elegant.

536
00:38:59,053 --> 00:39:01,388
Though on this particular occasion...

537
00:39:02,848 --> 00:39:04,558
...ultimately incorrect.

538
00:39:26,206 --> 00:39:29,251
- You're still here.
- I'm still here.

539
00:39:30,627 --> 00:39:31,586
Why?

540
00:39:32,629 --> 00:39:35,382
ALICIA: I'm wondering, Professor Nash...

541
00:39:37,175 --> 00:39:39,177
...if I can ask you to dinner.

542
00:39:43,390 --> 00:39:45,267
You do eat, don't you?

543
00:39:45,517 --> 00:39:47,852
On occasion, yeah.

544
00:39:47,936 --> 00:39:50,647
Table for one.
Prometheus alone chained to the rock...

545
00:39:50,730 --> 00:39:53,441
...with the bird circling overhead,
you know how it is.

546
00:39:53,525 --> 00:39:54,484
[Chuckles]

547
00:39:56,278 --> 00:39:59,447
No, I expect that you wouldn't know...

548
00:40:02,367 --> 00:40:06,621
Leave your address with my office.
I'll pick you up Friday...

549
00:40:07,205 --> 00:40:09,749
...at 8:00 and we'll eat.

550
00:40:17,966 --> 00:40:22,304
One more thing. Do you have a name,
or should I just keep calling you "miss"?

551
00:40:24,973 --> 00:40:26,141
JOHN: Governor...

552
00:40:26,266 --> 00:40:28,768
...may I present...
- Miss Alicia Larde.

553
00:40:30,729 --> 00:40:33,481
PHOTOGRAPHER:
Professor, please. You and the governor.

554
00:40:35,817 --> 00:40:37,945
Wait, one second. I'm sorry.

555
00:40:39,030 --> 00:40:42,408
ALICIA: I want a copy of this.
First big date and all, you know.

556
00:40:43,034 --> 00:40:45,745
<i>So, you boys need to look good... </i>

557
00:40:47,038 --> 00:40:51,375
...which is not a state
you find yourselves in altogether naturally.

558
00:40:55,171 --> 00:40:58,132
There. Better.

559
00:40:58,966 --> 00:41:02,053
- I'm surprising him.
- You just keep on surprising him.

560
00:41:02,136 --> 00:41:03,512
Professor.

561
00:41:10,269 --> 00:41:12,355
[Ambient party noises]

562
00:41:20,696 --> 00:41:22,573
God must be a painter.

563
00:41:23,616 --> 00:41:25,993
<i>Why else would we have so many colors? </i>

564
00:41:28,996 --> 00:41:30,539
So you're a painter?

565
00:41:31,999 --> 00:41:34,377
That's not actually what I said...

566
00:41:35,002 --> 00:41:38,464
...but, yes, I am.

567
00:41:47,974 --> 00:41:49,100
ALICIA: Here.

568
00:41:50,559 --> 00:41:51,560
Me.

569
00:41:52,061 --> 00:41:53,146
Your date.

570
00:41:55,649 --> 00:41:58,235
Practice human interaction
and social comportment.

571
00:41:58,318 --> 00:42:00,404
ALICIA: [Laughing] That's a plan.

572
00:42:03,824 --> 00:42:05,951
Champagne would be lovely.

573
00:42:07,995 --> 00:42:09,413
<i>I'll be outside. </i>

574
00:42:10,122 --> 00:42:12,249
I will get the champagne.

575
00:42:20,799 --> 00:42:22,175
ALICIA: Oh, thank you.

576
00:42:23,719 --> 00:42:25,220
Thank you for that.

577
00:42:25,304 --> 00:42:26,763
No, keep it.

578
00:42:27,431 --> 00:42:30,434
I believe in deciding things
will be good luck.

579
00:42:31,268 --> 00:42:33,729
- Do you?
- No.

580
00:42:34,855 --> 00:42:36,857
I don't believe in luck.

581
00:42:41,153 --> 00:42:43,864
But I do believe
in assigning value to things.

582
00:42:45,198 --> 00:42:47,034
Oh.

583
00:42:54,458 --> 00:42:56,501
ALICIA: I once tried to count them all.

584
00:42:58,003 --> 00:43:02,174
I actually made it to 4,348.

585
00:43:04,259 --> 00:43:06,094
You are exceptionally odd.

586
00:43:06,678 --> 00:43:09,556
I bet you're very popular with the girls.

587
00:43:15,396 --> 00:43:17,273
A pair of odd ducks, then.

588
00:43:17,690 --> 00:43:20,276
Mmm.

589
00:43:23,071 --> 00:43:24,489
Pick a shape.

590
00:43:26,574 --> 00:43:27,742
What?

591
00:43:28,868 --> 00:43:31,788
Pick a shape, an animal, anything.

592
00:43:33,873 --> 00:43:34,916
Okay.

593
00:43:36,376 --> 00:43:37,669
An umbrella.

594
00:44:02,026 --> 00:44:04,112
[Poignant instrumental music]

595
00:44:15,790 --> 00:44:17,500
Do it again.

596
00:44:18,543 --> 00:44:19,544
Do it again.

597
00:44:19,627 --> 00:44:23,214
JOHN: All right. What would you like?
ALICIA: Do an octopus.

598
00:45:11,263 --> 00:45:14,892
[Dramatic instrumental music]

599
00:46:47,527 --> 00:46:50,238
[Dog barks]

600
00:47:12,678 --> 00:47:14,305
[Alicia chuckles]

601
00:47:14,388 --> 00:47:16,557
ALICIA: You don't talk much, do you?

602
00:47:16,682 --> 00:47:19,226
JOHN: I can't talk to you
about my work, Alicia.

603
00:47:20,311 --> 00:47:21,938
I don't mean work.

604
00:47:26,651 --> 00:47:28,736
I find that polishing my interactions...

605
00:47:28,819 --> 00:47:32,406
...in order to make them sociable
requires a tremendous effort.

606
00:47:33,950 --> 00:47:36,827
I have a tendency
to expedite information flow...

607
00:47:38,955 --> 00:47:40,456
...by being direct.

608
00:47:42,291 --> 00:47:45,461
- I often don't get a pleasant result.
- Try me.

609
00:47:47,838 --> 00:47:48,965
All right.

610
00:47:53,511 --> 00:47:55,137
I find you attractive.

611
00:47:56,639 --> 00:48:00,559
Your aggressive moves towards me
indicate that you feel the same way.

612
00:48:01,102 --> 00:48:05,940
But still, ritual requires that we continue
with a number of platonic activities...

613
00:48:06,148 --> 00:48:08,025
...before we have sex.

614
00:48:08,734 --> 00:48:11,237
I am proceeding with those activities...

615
00:48:11,654 --> 00:48:13,698
...but in point of actual fact...

616
00:48:13,781 --> 00:48:18,035
...all I really want to do is have intercourse
with you as soon as possible.

617
00:48:20,122 --> 00:48:22,249
Are you going to slap me now?

618
00:48:46,940 --> 00:48:48,692
How was that result?

619
00:49:06,043 --> 00:49:07,586
MARCEE: What are you doing?

620
00:49:11,924 --> 00:49:16,053
Trying to isolate patterned reoccurrences
within periodicals over time.

621
00:49:16,219 --> 00:49:17,304
And you?

622
00:49:17,512 --> 00:49:19,348
You talk funny, Mr. Nash.

623
00:49:24,269 --> 00:49:25,604
Do I know you?

624
00:49:26,104 --> 00:49:29,399
My uncle says you're very smart
but not very nice...

625
00:49:29,608 --> 00:49:32,319
...so I shouldn't pay no mind
if you're mean to me.

626
00:49:32,402 --> 00:49:34,363
And who might your uncle be?

627
00:49:34,446 --> 00:49:36,157
CHARLES: The prodigal roommate...

628
00:49:37,116 --> 00:49:38,284
...returns.

629
00:49:38,868 --> 00:49:40,536
[Chuckles]

630
00:49:42,747 --> 00:49:44,791
JOHN: Come here, Charles.

631
00:49:50,588 --> 00:49:54,008
My sister got herself killed in a car crash.

632
00:49:55,718 --> 00:49:57,387
Not too far now, Marcee!

633
00:49:58,221 --> 00:50:02,725
<i>Her cowboy husband was too drunk</i>
<i>to know that he was too drunk to drive. </i>

634
00:50:02,809 --> 00:50:04,852
So, I took her in.

635
00:50:06,729 --> 00:50:10,066
- She's so small.
- She's young. That's how they come.

636
00:50:12,610 --> 00:50:14,070
I'm at Harvard...

637
00:50:14,696 --> 00:50:17,031
...doing the great author's workshop.

638
00:50:17,323 --> 00:50:19,200
D.H. bloody Lawrence.

639
00:50:19,450 --> 00:50:22,120
I really do think
you should buy yourself a new book.

640
00:50:22,203 --> 00:50:23,871
[Chuckles]

641
00:50:24,414 --> 00:50:26,916
CHARLES: Well, I've been reading
a lot about you.

642
00:50:28,209 --> 00:50:29,669
How are you, John?

643
00:50:30,670 --> 00:50:33,339
At first, all my work here was trivial...

644
00:50:33,756 --> 00:50:36,092
...but a new assignment came up and...

645
00:50:36,926 --> 00:50:38,928
I can't really tell you any details.

646
00:50:39,012 --> 00:50:41,306
Top secret? Black bag? Black ops?

647
00:50:41,806 --> 00:50:43,391
Something like that.

648
00:50:43,808 --> 00:50:46,394
- And...
- Yes?

649
00:50:47,812 --> 00:50:49,731
Well, I met a girl.

650
00:50:49,939 --> 00:50:51,733
- No! A human girl?
- Homo sapien.

651
00:50:51,816 --> 00:50:54,612
- A biped?
- Yep. And contrary to all probabilities...

652
00:50:54,695 --> 00:50:57,656
...she finds me attractive
on a number of different levels.

653
00:50:58,198 --> 00:51:00,159
God, that's wonderful.

654
00:51:00,868 --> 00:51:03,704
There's no accounting for taste, is there?

655
00:51:06,957 --> 00:51:09,835
- Should I marry her?
- Oh, God. Right.

656
00:51:11,545 --> 00:51:15,341
I mean, everything's going well.
The job is fine. I have enough money.

657
00:51:15,424 --> 00:51:17,092
It all seems to add up.

658
00:51:18,636 --> 00:51:20,763
But how do you know for sure?

659
00:51:22,598 --> 00:51:24,558
Nothing's ever for sure, John.

660
00:51:25,893 --> 00:51:28,228
That's the only sure thing I do know.

661
00:51:34,818 --> 00:51:36,320
WAITER: Good evening.

662
00:51:43,285 --> 00:51:47,081
JOHN: Alicia, please don't be angry.
I just lost track of time at work...

663
00:51:48,624 --> 00:51:50,292
JOHN: . . Again.
ALICIA: Mm-hmm.

664
00:51:51,835 --> 00:51:53,003
I'm sorry.

665
00:51:53,712 --> 00:51:55,714
I didn't have time to wrap it.

666
00:51:56,882 --> 00:51:58,634
Happy birthday.

667
00:52:02,346 --> 00:52:06,725
JOHN: The refractive faces of the glass
create a full wavelength dispersal...

668
00:52:06,809 --> 00:52:08,686
<i>... so if you look inside, you can see... </i>

669
00:52:08,769 --> 00:52:11,523
ALICIA: Every possible color.
JOHN: Every possible color.

670
00:52:11,606 --> 00:52:12,691
Yeah.

671
00:52:12,774 --> 00:52:16,778
Remember you said that time, God must
be a painter because of all the colors?

672
00:52:16,861 --> 00:52:19,239
At the governor's house you said that.

673
00:52:20,740 --> 00:52:22,909
I didn't think you were listening.

674
00:52:25,161 --> 00:52:26,788
I was listening.

675
00:52:33,628 --> 00:52:35,589
It's beautiful.

676
00:52:40,677 --> 00:52:42,429
[Both chuckle]

677
00:52:51,813 --> 00:52:55,025
Alicia, does our relationship
warrant long-term commitment?

678
00:52:55,108 --> 00:52:59,279
Because I need some kind of proof,
some kind of verifiable, empirical data.

679
00:53:02,991 --> 00:53:04,701
[Nervous laughter]

680
00:53:05,493 --> 00:53:08,163
I'm sorry, just give me a moment...

681
00:53:09,122 --> 00:53:12,125
...to redefine my girlish notions
of romance.

682
00:53:15,879 --> 00:53:17,172
A proof?

683
00:53:17,797 --> 00:53:19,382
Verifiable data.

684
00:53:21,051 --> 00:53:22,260
Okay.

685
00:53:25,764 --> 00:53:27,725
Well, how big is the universe?

686
00:53:28,017 --> 00:53:29,101
Infinite.

687
00:53:29,435 --> 00:53:30,603
ALICIA: How do you know?

688
00:53:30,686 --> 00:53:34,065
- Because all the data indicates it.
- But it hasn't been proven yet?

689
00:53:34,148 --> 00:53:36,859
You haven't seen it.
How do you know for sure?

690
00:53:37,902 --> 00:53:39,946
I don't, I just believe it.

691
00:53:42,865 --> 00:53:45,034
It's the same with love, I guess.

692
00:53:52,667 --> 00:53:53,793
Now...

693
00:53:54,502 --> 00:53:56,671
...the part that you don't know...

694
00:53:58,673 --> 00:54:00,633
...is if I want to marry you.

695
00:54:06,222 --> 00:54:10,017
[Indistinct chatter and laughter]

696
00:54:15,606 --> 00:54:18,234
[Applause]

697
00:54:22,196 --> 00:54:24,031
Smile for the camera!

698
00:54:29,120 --> 00:54:30,621
Well done!

699
00:54:32,790 --> 00:54:34,458
Congratulations.

700
00:54:35,001 --> 00:54:36,669
WOMAN: You look beautiful.

701
00:54:37,962 --> 00:54:39,338
SOL: Hi, how are you?

702
00:54:46,221 --> 00:54:48,181
WOMAN: Bye-bye.
MAN: 'Bye, now.

703
00:54:50,684 --> 00:54:51,852
<i>Be safe! </i>

704
00:54:59,818 --> 00:55:01,903
[Gate opens]

705
00:55:02,321 --> 00:55:04,239
CAMBRIDGE, MA - OCTOBER 1954

706
00:55:21,465 --> 00:55:23,300
Get in. Hurry.

707
00:55:26,929 --> 00:55:28,764
They're following us.

708
00:55:33,101 --> 00:55:36,480
- Who is following us?
- The drop has been compromised.

709
00:55:37,189 --> 00:55:38,732
PARCHER: Get down!

710
00:55:39,399 --> 00:55:41,234
Stay down.

711
00:55:46,281 --> 00:55:49,493
[Horns honking]

712
00:55:49,576 --> 00:55:51,954
[Tires screeching]

713
00:56:01,297 --> 00:56:03,925
[Gunfire]

714
00:56:09,097 --> 00:56:11,474
PARCHER: Take this.
JOHN: I ain't shooting anybody.

715
00:56:11,557 --> 00:56:14,227
- Take the goddamn gun!
- No!

716
00:56:16,354 --> 00:56:18,189
[Screams]

717
00:56:32,870 --> 00:56:34,998
PARCHER: You stay back. Don't move.

718
00:56:40,420 --> 00:56:42,171
[Screams]

719
00:56:45,049 --> 00:56:46,843
[Tires screech]

720
00:57:21,795 --> 00:57:22,922
ALICIA: John?

721
00:57:30,137 --> 00:57:31,221
Hi.

722
00:57:34,308 --> 00:57:35,976
Where were you?

723
00:57:38,854 --> 00:57:41,190
JOHN: Sol...
ALICIA: Yeah, I talked to Sol.

724
00:57:41,690 --> 00:57:44,068
<i>He said you left the office hours ago. </i>

725
00:57:47,279 --> 00:57:49,031
Why didn't you call me?

726
00:57:53,953 --> 00:57:55,412
Are you all right?

727
00:58:04,588 --> 00:58:05,714
ALICIA: Honey?

728
00:58:06,215 --> 00:58:07,967
[Bolt locks]

729
00:58:08,050 --> 00:58:09,301
ALICIA: John...

730
00:58:10,010 --> 00:58:12,680
...please, talk to me.
Tell me what happened.

731
00:58:14,056 --> 00:58:15,849
<i>John, open the door. </i>

732
00:58:17,601 --> 00:58:19,853
Come on, open the door! Let me in!

733
00:58:20,646 --> 00:58:22,022
Talk to me!

734
00:58:23,899 --> 00:58:25,484
John!

735
00:58:26,193 --> 00:58:28,028
ALICIA: [Shouts] Open this door!

736
00:58:30,781 --> 00:58:33,200
[Panting]

737
00:58:45,130 --> 00:58:47,048
WOMAN: Watch for cars, kids.

738
00:59:07,569 --> 00:59:09,821
[Door bangs shut]

739
00:59:29,174 --> 00:59:30,258
PARCHER: John.

740
00:59:32,052 --> 00:59:33,136
William.

741
00:59:33,762 --> 00:59:36,056
<i>This is not what I signed up for. </i>

742
00:59:36,181 --> 00:59:38,433
Every time a car backfires or a door slams...

743
00:59:38,516 --> 00:59:41,561
I understand better
than you could possibly imagine.

744
00:59:51,905 --> 00:59:53,824
You need to calm down, John.

745
00:59:54,742 --> 00:59:57,203
PARCHER: Now listen.
We're closing in on the bomb...

746
00:59:57,286 --> 00:59:59,497
<i>... in large part due to your work. </i>

747
00:59:59,580 --> 01:00:02,708
Now don't you think your fear
is a small price to pay?

748
01:00:02,875 --> 01:00:05,211
William, my circumstance has changed.

749
01:00:06,003 --> 01:00:07,463
Alicia's pregnant.

750
01:00:16,097 --> 01:00:18,474
I told you attachments were dangerous.

751
01:00:19,183 --> 01:00:21,102
<i>You chose to marry the girl. </i>

752
01:00:22,311 --> 01:00:24,230
<i>I did nothing to prevent it. </i>

753
01:00:27,108 --> 01:00:29,610
The best way to ensure
everybody's safety...

754
01:00:30,319 --> 01:00:32,196
...is for you to continue your work.

755
01:00:33,364 --> 01:00:34,657
Well, I'll just quit.

756
01:00:35,283 --> 01:00:36,284
You won't.

757
01:00:36,951 --> 01:00:38,077
Why would I not?

758
01:00:38,244 --> 01:00:41,372
Because I keep the Russians
from knowing you work for us.

759
01:00:42,081 --> 01:00:43,833
<i>You quit working for me... </i>

760
01:00:44,750 --> 01:00:46,210
...I quit working for you.

761
01:00:59,890 --> 01:01:02,059
Parcher!

762
01:01:07,398 --> 01:01:08,858
SOL: John, you all right?

763
01:01:30,255 --> 01:01:31,298
ALICIA: John?

764
01:01:31,465 --> 01:01:33,967
JOHN: [Angrily]
Turn it off! Turn off the light!

765
01:01:37,054 --> 01:01:38,472
Why would you do that?

766
01:01:39,139 --> 01:01:42,100
- Why would you turn the light on?
- What is wrong with you?

767
01:01:42,225 --> 01:01:44,102
You have to go to your sister's.

768
01:01:44,937 --> 01:01:48,231
JOHN: I left the car out in back.
Take Commonwealth, no side streets.

769
01:01:48,315 --> 01:01:49,608
Stay where it's crowded.

770
01:01:49,691 --> 01:01:51,318
ALICIA: John, I'm not going anywhere!

771
01:01:51,401 --> 01:01:53,904
JOHN: When you get to your sister's,
wait for my call.

772
01:01:53,987 --> 01:01:55,739
- Get your things.
- I'm not leaving!

773
01:01:55,822 --> 01:01:57,491
Stop! Stop it!

774
01:01:58,408 --> 01:01:59,660
JOHN: Please, Alicia.

775
01:02:02,412 --> 01:02:03,789
I'll explain when I can.

776
01:02:24,309 --> 01:02:27,438
[Dramatic instrumental music]

777
01:02:42,787 --> 01:02:45,373
HARVARD UNIVERSITY
NATIONAL MATHEMATICS CONFERENCE

778
01:02:51,296 --> 01:02:52,630
MARCEE: Uncle John!

779
01:02:53,131 --> 01:02:54,215
<i>Uncle John! </i>

780
01:02:55,174 --> 01:02:57,260
[Roars]

781
01:02:58,386 --> 01:03:00,179
Hey, baby girl! [Marcee giggles]

782
01:03:00,805 --> 01:03:02,807
Wow, someone needed a hug!

783
01:03:03,600 --> 01:03:05,977
I saw you on the slate,
and I thought to myself:

784
01:03:06,060 --> 01:03:10,356
"How can I miss seeing a guest lecture
by the inimitable John Nash?"

785
01:03:13,318 --> 01:03:14,611
CHARLES: What's wrong?

786
01:03:17,530 --> 01:03:20,533
I got myself into something.
I think I might need some help.

787
01:03:20,992 --> 01:03:22,994
Now you tell me, what is it?

788
01:03:23,161 --> 01:03:24,871
WOMAN: Professor Nash!

789
01:03:25,246 --> 01:03:26,372
Welcome!

790
01:03:28,791 --> 01:03:29,792
After?

791
01:03:37,967 --> 01:03:42,972
JOHN: So, we see that the zeroes
of the Riemann Zeta function...

792
01:03:43,556 --> 01:03:45,809
...correspond to singularities...

793
01:03:46,101 --> 01:03:48,312
<i>... in space-time... </i>

794
01:03:49,063 --> 01:03:51,440
Singularities in space-time then...

795
01:03:55,152 --> 01:03:57,196
And conventional number theory...

796
01:03:59,657 --> 01:04:03,911
It breaks down
in the face of relativistic exploration.

797
01:04:12,962 --> 01:04:16,590
[Ominous instrumental music]

798
01:04:20,219 --> 01:04:23,222
Sometimes our expectations
are betrayed by the numbers.

799
01:04:25,099 --> 01:04:29,770
Variables are impossible
to assign any rational value.

800
01:04:50,416 --> 01:04:52,001
MAN: Professor Nash!

